.SH "NAME"
profile \- files used for the startup of login/interactive shells
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.sp
When a shell is started, a few files get read. The order used on Mutiny systems is documented here,
and the default actions of the profile files given is explained here.
.SS "Order"
.sp
If the shell is a login shell, the following files are read:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 1.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 1." 4.2
.\}
\fI/etc/profile\fP
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 2.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 2." 4.2
.\}
\fI/share/profile.d/*.sh\fP \- system\-maintained profile files installed by the package manager,
praxis(7).
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 3.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 3." 4.2
.\}
A shell\-specific, admin\-managed profile:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
On ksh(1), this is \fI/etc/ksh/profile\fP.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
On sh(1), this is \fI/etc/sh/profile\fP.
.RE
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 4.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 4." 4.2
.\}
\fI~/.profile\fP. If a shell is not a login shell, no further files are read.
.RE
.sp
If the shell is an interactive shell, the following files are read:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 1.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 1." 4.2
.\}
A shell\-specific, admin\-managed rc file:
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04' 2.\h'+01'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP " 2." 4.2
.\}
A user\-maintained, shell\-specific rc file:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
On ksh(1), this is either \fI~/.kshrc\fP or \fI~/.config/ksh/rc\fP. \fI~/.kshrc\fP takes priority.
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
On sh(1), this is either \fI~/.shrc\fP or \fI~/.config/sh/rc\fP. \fI~/.shrc\fP takes priority.
.RE
.RE
.sp
On both ksh(1) and sh(1), the file that will be used is specified via the $ENV environment variable.
See their respective manuals for details on that.
.sp
Lastly, if it is an interactive login shell, both sets are read in the order they are listed.
