.SH "GLOSSARY"
.sp
interactive shell
.RS 4
A shell that is started for the purpose of running commands. That is, it prints a prompt, the
user is expected to be typing commands into it and so on. This corresponds to the \fB\-i\fP flag.
.RE
.sp
login shell
.RS 4
A shell started with the \fB\-l\fP flag, or with its argv[0] starting with a dash.
Less obtusely, this means a shell started by a variety of methods:
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
By a user logging in via login(1), from a virtual terminal
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
By a user logging in via ssh(1), interactively
.RE
.sp
.RS 4
.ie n \{\
\h'-04'\(bu\h'+03'\c
.\}
.el \{\
.  sp -1
.  IP \(bu 2.3
.\}
Some terminals can spawn login shells if you tell them to.
.RE
.RE
